<n-docbody><doc bill="Y"><content.metadata.block><cmd.identifiers><cmd.cites><cmd.second.line.cite><bop/><bos/>Ga. Evidence § 9:36<eos/><eop/></cmd.second.line.cite></cmd.cites></cmd.identifiers></content.metadata.block><prop.block><prop.head toc-guid=""><bop/><bos/><headtext>Agnor&apos;s Georgia Evidence</headtext><eos/><eop/></prop.head><content.metadata.block><cmd.dates><cmd.currency.default iso.d="20191101"><bop/><bos/>November 2019 Update<eos/><eop/></cmd.currency.default></cmd.dates></content.metadata.block><author.line><bop/><bos/><author>Ana Marcela Rountree</author><eos/><eop/></author.line><prop.head toc-guid="I288e2b10630a11eab5989292d3e01631"><bop/><bos/><label.name>Chapter</label.name><label.designator>9.</label.designator><headtext>Hearsay</headtext><eos/><eop/></prop.head></prop.block><message.block><include.copyright n-include_collection="w_wlnv_msg" n-include_guid="I1DA35ED81DD211B281BAD200220BDFCA">Copr. (C) West 2005 No Claim to Orig. U.S. Govt. Works</include.copyright></message.block><section><section.front><doc.title toc-guid="Id720b366682311ea83aee46e6decbb85"><head parent="doc.title"><bop/><bos/><label.name>§ </label.name><label.designator>9:36.</label.designator><headtext>Reputation</headtext><eos/><eop/></head></doc.title></section.front><section.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017195" w-seq-number="00001" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="USFRER803" w-pub-number="1000607" ID="I521cf7e07fc011ea988285db8533e975">Fed. R. Evid. 803(19)</cite.query> provides for the admission of reputation evidence concerning family or personal history. <eos/><bos/>Also, <cite.query w-src-number="0287017195" w-seq-number="00002" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="USFRER803" w-pub-number="1000607" ID="I521cf7e17fc011ea988285db8533e975">Rule 803(20)</cite.query> excepts from hearsay reputation evidence as to a person&apos;s character in the community. <eos/><bos/>In these areas, the federal and Georgia practice are generally the same.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>Reputation evidence is an exception to the hearsay rule and is most frequently used to prove character.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="Ic5b1e5807fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">1</footnote.reference>]</paratext><eos/><eop/></para></section.body></section><footnote.block><footnote ID="Ic5b1e5807fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>1</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017195" w-serial-number="1907012308" w-seq-number="00003" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000710" ID="I521d94227fc011ea988285db8533e975">Moore v. Dozier, 128 Ga. 90, 57 S.E. 110 (1907)</cite.query>. <eos/><bos/>But reputation or opinion of the neighborhood cannot be used to prove insanity. <eos/><bos/><cite.query w-src-number="0287017195" w-serial-number="1977114054" w-seq-number="00004" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I521d94257fc011ea988285db8533e975">Cooper v. State, 238 Ga. 502, 233 S.E.2d 762 (1977)</cite.query>; <cite.query w-src-number="0287017195" w-serial-number="1979128800" w-seq-number="00005" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I521d94287fc011ea988285db8533e975">Fireman&apos;s Fund Ins. Co. v. Smith, 151 Ga. App. 270, 259 S.E.2d 675 (1979)</cite.query>, held that reputation in the community as to marital status was admissible.<eos/><page no="342"/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote></footnote.block><content.metadata.block><cmd.royalty><cmd.copyright><bop/><bos/>Westlaw. © 2019 Thomson Reuters.  <eos/><bos/>No Claim to Orig. U.S. Govt. <eos/><bos/>Works.<eos/><eop/></cmd.copyright></cmd.royalty><cmd.identifiers><cmd.cites><cmd.first.line.cite><bop/><bos/>GAEVIDENCE § 9:36<eos/><eop/></cmd.first.line.cite></cmd.cites></cmd.identifiers></content.metadata.block></doc></n-docbody>
